But wait, the original code uses a priority_queue<PII> which, by default, sorts in descending order. So the largest element comes first. To get the smallest distance processed first, the code uses negative distances. The initial push is q.push({0, n}), which is correct since 0 is the smallest, but stored as -0 (same as 0).
